aa(lp29
VBut they didn't spend a lot of time reliving the glory days.
p30
aVFor the most part, everyone was just trying to survive.
p31
aVIt's a lot harder than you might think.
p32
aVContrary to what most people think,
p33
aVpeople don't pay, taxpayers don't pay, for your life
p34
aVwhen you're in prison. You've got to pay for your own life.
p35
aVYou've got to pay for your soap, your deodorant,
p36
aVtoothbrush, toothpaste, all of it.
p37
aVAnd it's hard for a couple of reasons.
p38
aVFirst, everything's marked up 30 to 50 percent
p39
aVfrom what you'd pay on the street,
p40
aVand second, you don't make a lot of money.
p41
aVI unloaded trucks. That was my full-time job,
p42
aVunloading trucks at a food warehouse,
p43
aVfor $5.25, not an hour, but per month.
p44
aa(lp45
VSo how do you survive?
p46
aVWell, you learn to hustle, all kinds of hustles.
p47
aVThere's legal hustles.
p48
aVYou pay everything in stamps. Those are the currency.
p49
aVYou charge another inmate to clean his cell.
p50
aVThere's sort of illegal hustles, like you run a barbershop out of your cell.
p51
aVThere's pretty illegal hustles: You run a tattoo parlor out of your own cell.
p52
aVAnd there's very illegal hustles, which you smuggle in,
p53
aVyou get smuggled in, drugs, pornography,
p54
aVcell phones, and just as in the outer world,
p55
aVthere's a risk-reward tradeoff, so the riskier the enterprise,
p56
aVthe more profitable it can potentially be.
p57
aVYou want a cigarette in prison? Three to five dollars.
p58
aVYou want an old-fashioned cell phone that you flip open
p59
aVand is about as big as your head? Three hundred bucks.
p60
aVYou want a dirty magazine?
p61
aVWell, it can be as much as 1,000 dollars.
p62
aa(lp63
VSo as you can probably tell, one of the defining aspects
p64
aVof prison life is ingenuity.
p65
aVWhether it was concocting delicious meals
p66
aVfrom stolen scraps from the warehouse,
p67
aVsculpting people's hair with toenail clippers,
p68
aVor constructing weights from boulders in laundry bags
p69
aVtied on to tree limbs, prisoners learn how to make do with less,
p70
aVand many of them want to take this ingenuity
p71
aVthat they've learned to the outside
p72
aVand start restaurants, barber shops,
p73
aVpersonal training businesses.
p74
aa(lp75
VBut there's no training, nothing to prepare them for that,
p76
aVno rehabilitation at all in prison,
p77
aVno one to help them write a business plan,
